I think there’s a useful insight in that framing, as long as we distinguish the metaphor from the biology.

A reflex is a good carrier because it has properties you care about:

* It is fast.
* It often operates with little conscious deliberation.
* It is reliable once established.
* It can be triggered by cues rather than lengthy reasoning.

In humans, many things become “compiled” in that way through repetition: reading, driving, martial arts, musical performance, even conversational habits. What began as explicit reasoning becomes a procedural pattern.

So if I translate your statement into cognitive terms:

“We’re using reflexes as carriers.”

I would hear:

“We’re trying to embed useful operators into procedural memory and automatic perception so they become available without reconstructing them from first principles every time.”

That lines up with your recurring emphasis on compression.

