The important distinction is that not every automatic behavior is a spinal reflex. Many “automatic” human skills are learned cortical and subcortical patterns rather than innate reflexes. But functionally, they serve a similar role: they let the system respond quickly because previous computation has been compiled into an efficient pathway.

That also suggests an architectural principle:

* Conscious reasoning discovers an operator.
* Practice compiles it.
* Automatic execution carries it into real-world behavior.

In that sense, the carrier isn’t only a word or a symbol. It can be a habit, a perceptual cue, a movement, or a way of seeing. Once internalized, the environment itself can trigger the operator without requiring the person to consciously reconstruct it each time.